<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Prunus</i> <i>subcordata</i> and/or <i>Prunus</i> <i>virginiana</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Ericameria</i> <i>nauseosa</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Frangula</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Rhus</i> <i>trilobata</i>, <i>Ribes</i> <i>cereum</i>, <i>Ribes</i> <i>velutinum</i>, <i>Rosa</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Rosa</i> <i>woodsii</i>, <i>Sambucus</i> <i>nigra</i>, <i>Symphoricarpos</i> <i>mollis</i> and <i>Toxicodendron</i> <i>diversilobum</i>. Associated herbs include <i>Bromus</i> <i>tectorum</i>, <i>Elymus</i> <i>elymoides</i> and <i>Leymus</i> <i>cinereus</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 8 m; canopy is open to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Prunus virginiana</i> >30% relative cover in the shrub layer (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
		<li><i>Prunus virginiana</i> >50% relative cover in the shrub layer; found in moist draws and dry ravines, sometimes on serpentinite (Buck-Diaz et al. 2012).</li>
		
		<li><i>Prunus virginiana</i> >50% relative cover in the shrub overstory. Other shrubs may be present at lower cover including <i>Rhamnus</i> spp., <i>Rosa californica, Sambucus nigra, Symphoricarpos mollis</i>, etc. (Evens and San 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Prunus subcordata</i> >60% relative cover in the shrub layer with <i>Ericameria nauseosa, Prunus virginiana</i>, and/or <i>Ribes velutinum</i> (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Rock outcrops, draws, stream terraces. Typically found on rocky, moderately steep to steep north-facing slopes. The USACE Wetland Inventory (2018 national list) recognizes <i>Prunus virginiana</i> as a FAC plant. </div>
</div>

        
