<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Prunus virginiana </i>is a deciduous, thicket-forming erect shrub or small tree to 8 m tall. Plants have a network of rhizomes and a deep root system. The inflorecences are showy, sometimes pendent, racemes of white flowers. Birds and mammals eat the fleshy drupes and may disperse seeds long distances. Plants often grow along fencerows. Two varieties of <i>Prunus virginiana</i> are known in North America: <i>P. virginiana</i> var. <i>virginiana</i> grows in the eastern US and Canada. The western variety, <i>P. virginiana</i> var. <i>demissa</i> is found along the west coast North America, and in the southwestern US. The western variety (var. <i>demissa</i>) is less treelike than the eastern variety (var. <i>virginiana</i> , and the fruits are dark red instead of blackish (Johnson 2000c, Welch 2002). Although <i>P. virginiana</i> var. <i>demissa</i> is native to California, var. <i>virginiana</i> is sometimes cultivated (The Jepson Manual 2012).<br/>
<br/>
In California, <i>Prunus virginiana</i> typically grows on rocky slopes, in canyons, scrubland, oak or pine woodlands and conifer forests. In San Diego county, <i>P. virginiana</i> is associated with other cold-deciduous shrubs such as <i>Rhamnus</i> spp., <i>Rosa californica, Sambucus nigra,</i> and <i>Symphoricarpos mollis</i> (Evens and San 2005). In central California, stands of this alliance are primarily found in moist draws and dry ravines, particularly in the coast ranges adjacent to the central valley (Buck-Diaz et al. 2012). In the Modoc region, stands of <i>P. virginiana</i> are typically found on rocky, moderately steep to steep, north-facing slopes (Boul et al. 2021b). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Prunus subcordata</i> is a deciduous, thicket-forming shrub or small tree which may reach 2 to 7.5 meters in height, with stiff branches sometimes ending in thorny points. The inflorescences consist of showy, white to pink flowers in clusters of 1 to 7. Fruits are red to reddish purple or occasionally yellow, fleshy or dry drupes (Stuart and Sawyer 2001). Several varieties have been separated based primarily on variability in the fruit: var. <i>kelloggii</i> bears large, sweet, yellow fruits; var. <i>rubicunda</i> bears smaller, bright red, bitter fruits; and var. <i>oregana</i> bears puberulent fruits from densely hairy ovaries. Study is needed to determine if these varieties merit recognition, herbaria specimen are few and collections are lacking (Flora of North America 1993+).<br/>
<br/>
The distribution of <i>Prunus subcordata</i> is restricted to California and southern Oregon. In California, it grows on rocky slopes or stream banks, in chaparral, pine-oak woodlands, or juniper-oak woodlands. Only a small number of <i>P. subcordata</i> stands have been sampled. In the Modoc region, stands of <i>P. subcordata</i> were found on the middle to upper portions of rocky, moderately steep, northeast-facing slopes. Associated species in these stands were typically sparse in cover and included <i>Juniperus occidentalis, Ericameria nauseosa, Prunus virginiana,</i> and<i> Ribes velutinum</i> (Boul et al. 2021b). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
