    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>Since sampling and mapping projects have not been completed for the entire state, probable or expected stands mentioned in a given region are based on CCH and Calflora records (Consortium of California Herbaria 2018; Calflora 2018) paired with the known presence of habitat conditions suitable for stands to form.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ac, Ae). Probable stands in limited areas of this region.</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ae, Ag, Aj-l, At). Expected stands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Ga-p). Stands have been sampled and mapped all throughout this region.  Typically found on north-facing, rocky, and steep slopes.  (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Da-b). Probable stands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Ba-b, Bd-e). Mapped and recorded stands are present in mountainous areas throughout the region (Boul et al. 2021b).  A few mapped stands fell within the bounds of the Madeleine Plain.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea, Ec-d, Eg, Ej, Em-n, Ep, Es-t). Expected stands throughout region.  Sampled stands in the Doyle-Loyalton project area, with stands expected to be mapped upon completion (Ratchford et al. 2021b, in progress).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fc-e). Some recorded stands throughout the region, including within Sequoia National Forest and the Wind Wolves Preserve (Ratchford et al. 2021a, in progress).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba, Bd-e, Bg-h, Bo). Evens and San (2005) described the alliance as disjunct stands at Volcan Mountain in the Palomar-Cuyamaca Peak region.  Expected stands in other subsections.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Df-h, Dj). Expected stands throughout this region;  recorded stands in Lava Beds National Monument (DiPaolo et al. 2015).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Prunus virginiana</i> foliage can be used as browse by large mammals, including occasionally by livestock such as cattle and sheep. Fresh foliage can cause poisoning in livestock, but consumption of fatal quantities is rare. The fruits are eaten by small mammals and are an important resource for several species of birds. Plants can act as habitat and/or cover for birds, mammals and livestock as well as providing erosion control and thermal cover in fisheries (Johnson 200c).

<i>Prunus virginiana</i> can be top-killed by fire but will resprout prolifically. Seed germination is also improved by heat, which may add to postfire regeneration. Following fire, <i>P. virginiana</i> shrubs appear to generally increase in number and density before returning to prefire condition after a number of years (Johnson 2000c). </div>
</div>

    

    

